 {"id":"asupersync-0wl","title":"Implement test oracle: no_obligation_leaks invariant checker","description":"## Purpose
Implement a test oracle that verifies the "no obligation leaks" invariant: all obligations (SendPermit, Ack, Lease, IoOp) are either committed or aborted before their owning region closes.

## The Invariant
From asupersync_plan_v4.md:
> Permits/acks/leases must be committed or aborted; no silent drops

Formally: `∀o ∈ obligations: state(o) ∈ {Committed, Aborted}` at region close

## Obligation Lifecycle
```
Created → [Committed | Aborted]
```

An obligation leak occurs when an obligation exists in Created state when its region closes.

## Oracle Design

```rust
pub struct ObligationLeakOracle {
    // Tracks all obligation lifecycle events
    creates: Vec<(ObligationId, ObligationKind, RegionId, Time)>,
    resolutions: Vec<(ObligationId, ObligationState, Time)>,  // Committed or Aborted
    region_closes: Vec<(RegionId, Time)>,
}

impl ObligationLeakOracle {
    /// Called when reserve() creates obligation
    pub fn on_create(&mut self, id: ObligationId, kind: ObligationKind, region: RegionId, time: Time);

    /// Called when commit() or abort() resolves obligation
    pub fn on_resolve(&mut self, id: ObligationId, state: ObligationState, time: Time);

    /// Called when region closes
    pub fn on_region_close(&mut self, region: RegionId, time: Time);

    /// Verify invariant holds
    pub fn check(&self) -> Result<(), ObligationLeakViolation>;
}
```

## Violation Detection
```rust
pub struct ObligationLeakViolation {
    pub region: RegionId,
    pub leaked_obligations: Vec<ObligationId>,
    pub kinds: Vec<ObligationKind>,  // SendPermit, Ack, Lease, IoOp
    pub region_close_time: Time,
}
```

A violation occurs when:
1. Region R closes at time T
2. ∃ obligation O in R with state ∉ {Committed, Aborted} at time T

## Obligation Kinds and Their Semantics
| Kind | Created By | Committed By | Aborted By |
|------|-----------|--------------|------------|
| SendPermit | tx.reserve() | permit.send() | permit.abort() or Drop |
| Ack | receive message | ack.commit() | ack.nack() |
| Lease | acquire_lease() | lease.release() | lease.expire() |
| IoOp | io.start() | io.complete() | io.cancel() |

## Linear Type Enforcement
The oracle complements Rust's ownership model:
- In ideal code, obligations are `#[must_use]` and consumed exactly once
- Oracle catches runtime violations that slip through static checks
- Particularly important for dynamic scenarios (vec of obligations, etc.)

## Testing the Oracle
1. **Correct case**: All obligations resolved → check passes
2. **Leak cases by kind**: Each obligation type can leak → check catches
3. **Nested regions**: Inner region obligations must resolve before inner closes
4. **Cancellation**: Cancelled tasks must still resolve their obligations (via abort)

## References
- asupersync_plan_v4.md: §4.4 Obligation Registry, §6.5 Two-Phase Operations
- asupersync_v4_formal_semantics.md: Invariant I2 (obligation_resolved)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Oracle flags any leaked obligation (task completes with unresolved reserved obligations).
- Supports per-kind accounting (permits/acks/leases/ioops) and region-scoped checks.
- Diagnostics include obligation id, kind, holder task, and owning region.
- Deterministic; usable on both trace events and direct registry snapshots.
